00:52:47.570 --> 00:52:50.810
RAFAEL: So maybe have time
for one or two questions.

00:52:50.810 --> 00:52:53.240
And since I know
Nelson personally,

00:52:53.240 --> 00:52:57.360
I actually want to ask you a
personal question if I may.

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:00.830
You look back to a very
successful tech career.

00:53:00.830 --> 00:53:03.170
You retired from Google.

00:53:03.170 --> 00:53:05.870
You could be sitting on a
sailing boat in the Caribbean

00:53:05.870 --> 00:53:07.940
and enjoy retirement.

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:09.390
Maybe you do this.

00:53:09.390 --> 00:53:10.640
NELSON MATTOS: I do that, too.

00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:11.930
RAFAEL: Exactly.

00:53:11.930 --> 00:53:13.730
I saw you on a couple
of those pictures

00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:17.810
with really dirty hands,
like literally dirty hands.

00:53:17.810 --> 00:53:21.680
How does that feel, and what
does it give you personally?

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:23.840
NELSON MATTOS: It's
extremely difficult

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:26.480
to describe what
you feel when you

00:53:26.480 --> 00:53:29.540
are doing volunteer work,
particularly hands-on volunteer

00:53:29.540 --> 00:53:32.150
work in this area.

00:53:32.150 --> 00:53:35.450
All I can tell you is
it's extremely gratifying.

00:53:35.450 --> 00:53:37.970
It's extremely satisfying.

00:53:37.970 --> 00:53:41.480
The eyes of the
people there, the way

00:53:41.480 --> 00:53:46.190
they thank you, the way they
show gratitude for what you do,

00:53:46.190 --> 00:53:49.810
is so fulfilling.

00:53:49.810 --> 00:53:53.180
It's impossible to walk away.

00:53:53.180 --> 00:53:56.030
I came to Tanzania this
year for the second time.

00:53:56.030 --> 00:53:58.460
So there was a lot of
people that I have met.

00:53:58.460 --> 00:54:00.250
And it was an
incredible feeling.

00:54:00.250 --> 00:54:02.650
The moment I was
arriving in the village,

00:54:02.650 --> 00:54:05.470
I was feeling like
I'm back home.

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:08.080
And people were coming to
me, and how's your son,

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:10.390
and how's your wife,
and what about this,

00:54:10.390 --> 00:54:12.100
and what about that.

00:54:12.100 --> 00:54:13.920
We are fortunate.

00:54:13.920 --> 00:54:17.890
We in the developed
countries have grown in a way

00:54:17.890 --> 00:54:22.240
that we have distanced
ourselves from our communities.

00:54:22.240 --> 00:54:25.230
And they are extremely tight.

00:54:25.230 --> 00:54:26.730
And the moment you
arrive there, you

00:54:26.730 --> 00:54:28.000
are part of their community.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:30.310
You are part of their family.

00:54:30.310 --> 00:54:36.540
We tend to focus on us
first, second the family,

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:37.990
third the community.

00:54:37.990 --> 00:54:41.140
They are exactly the
opposite-- community first,

00:54:41.140 --> 00:54:44.170
my family second, me
as a person third.

00:54:44.170 --> 00:54:49.120
And it's incredible to see
somebody making a decision that

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:50.650
is not the best for
them personally,

00:54:50.650 --> 00:54:53.110
but it's the right thing
to do for the community.

00:54:53.110 --> 00:54:55.650
We would never do that.

00:54:55.650 --> 00:54:59.510
When we arrived this year-- and
last year was the same thing--

00:54:59.510 --> 00:55:02.940
you get to the institute where
we actually stay overnight.

00:55:02.940 --> 00:55:05.220
About 300 meters
from the institute,

00:55:05.220 --> 00:55:08.790
there were probably 1,000
people waiting for you.

00:55:08.790 --> 00:55:11.080
And you get out of this bus.

00:55:11.080 --> 00:55:12.490
Everybody is dancing.

00:55:12.490 --> 00:55:15.080
Everybody is singing,
welcoming you.

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:17.280
And you are walking
along this path.

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:19.800
There is the traditional
dancers dancing

00:55:19.800 --> 00:55:21.510
their traditional things.

00:55:21.510 --> 00:55:22.470
You walk a little bit.

00:55:22.470 --> 00:55:24.570
There is the choir
from the church,

00:55:24.570 --> 00:55:26.520
and then the choir
from the school,

00:55:26.520 --> 00:55:31.560
and then the midwives all
thanking you and welcoming you

00:55:31.560 --> 00:55:32.420
back home.

00:55:32.420 --> 00:55:36.060
So you really feel like you
are the sun that is coming back

00:55:36.060 --> 00:55:38.850
home for five to six years.

00:55:38.850 --> 00:55:40.200
It's impossible.

00:55:40.200 --> 00:55:42.744
I don't want to talk some more
because I will start crying.

00:55:42.744 --> 00:55:43.410
RAFAEL: Exactly.

00:55:43.410 --> 00:55:44.493
I think it's very telling.

00:55:44.493 --> 00:55:45.750
That's exactly why I asked.

00:55:45.750 --> 00:55:47.610
It sounds like it's
very rewarding for you.

00:55:47.610 --> 00:55:50.130
And that's very impressive, and
I think touches a lot of us.

00:55:50.130 --> 00:55:51.213
Thank you so much, Nelson.

00:55:51.213 --> 00:55:53.610
Maybe the final question
to you, Marianne.

00:55:53.610 --> 00:55:55.110
So from listening
to all of this,

00:55:55.110 --> 00:55:57.990
it sounds like you
established maybe a best

00:55:57.990 --> 00:56:00.870
practice in how to do this.

00:56:00.870 --> 00:56:03.090
That's how I understood
what you're saying here.

00:56:03.090 --> 00:56:05.230
I wonder, in terms
of vision and future,

00:56:05.230 --> 00:56:08.130
do you personally think
you want to stay at that,

00:56:08.130 --> 00:56:10.590
and you maybe want to grow
Karimu as it is today,

00:56:10.590 --> 00:56:14.050
or would you even
see potentially maybe

00:56:14.050 --> 00:56:16.440
to roll out those best
practices for other NGOs

00:56:16.440 --> 00:56:19.410
and maybe grow, in
a sense, the method?

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:21.990
MARIANNE KENT-STOLL: I think
that's an excellent question.

00:56:21.990 --> 00:56:24.250
There's a company
called Quantify

00:56:24.250 --> 00:56:29.400
in Santa Cruz that has been
giving us a $20,000 matching

00:56:29.400 --> 00:56:30.990
grant every year.

00:56:30.990 --> 00:56:34.170
And they have
endorsed this model.

00:56:34.170 --> 00:56:37.080
But the owner, Ken
Terry, always says

00:56:37.080 --> 00:56:40.800
you should mentor other
people, because you

00:56:40.800 --> 00:56:46.350
could have replicated
models in other villages.

00:56:46.350 --> 00:56:48.720
And it does take
time, because you

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:51.330
have to stay in this
same community--

00:56:51.330 --> 00:56:54.300
not creating dependency because
you don't stay in one school,

00:56:54.300 --> 00:56:56.380
but you move from
school to school,

00:56:56.380 --> 00:56:59.770
from medical center to
other medical center.

00:56:59.770 --> 00:57:02.380
But you have to stay
in that community.

00:57:02.380 --> 00:57:07.080
So I would like to
expand, but like this.

00:57:07.080 --> 00:57:11.580
And also, I would like to be
able to mentor other people.

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:15.180
And this summer, we had the
opportunity to mentor David

00:57:15.180 --> 00:57:18.060
Newman and his wife,
Laura, who came and stayed

00:57:18.060 --> 00:57:19.140
some time in the village.

00:57:19.140 --> 00:57:22.410
Because they just started an
NGO, and they want to know how

00:57:22.410 --> 00:57:23.040
we do it.

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:25.630
And they watched us
for about five days.

00:57:25.630 --> 00:57:28.290
And it was very, very
gratifying to have

00:57:28.290 --> 00:57:32.080
them ask us questions, to walk
with us through the village.

00:57:32.080 --> 00:57:35.610
So I'd like to continue
replicating that model,

00:57:35.610 --> 00:57:40.680
with the idea with small
things, with concentrated work,

00:57:40.680 --> 00:57:43.130
you can do really,
really great things.

00:57:43.130 --> 00:57:45.130
NELSON MATTOS: Let me add
to what Marianne said.

00:57:45.130 --> 00:57:47.280
I think Karimu has two goals.

00:57:47.280 --> 00:57:50.730
In addition to increase
the impact in this region

00:57:50.730 --> 00:57:54.467
and slowly expand graphically,
the second big role--

00:57:54.467 --> 00:57:56.550
and I think this is probably
what will be the most

00:57:56.550 --> 00:57:57.500
powerful--

00:57:57.500 --> 00:58:00.090
is to create a new model
for social development.

00:58:00.090 --> 00:58:02.930
Given that the existing
model is falling apart,

00:58:02.930 --> 00:58:08.460
become a showcase of how you can
be doing successful development

00:58:08.460 --> 00:58:12.360
work and hopefully have
many, many other NGOs falling

00:58:12.360 --> 00:58:14.770
exactly the same principle.

00:58:14.770 --> 00:58:15.690
RAFAEL: Wonderful.

00:58:15.690 --> 00:58:17.719
Thanks again so much for
sharing this with us,

00:58:17.719 --> 00:58:19.260
and the trust, and
everything you do.

00:58:19.260 --> 00:58:21.030
Thank you so much.

